{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CwWH2y5NULwSLExAPYeUxX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.List;\n     5→import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;\n     6→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     7→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     8→import javax.inject.Named;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoStatus;\n    11→\n    12→/**\n    13→ * Handles tracking cargo. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    14→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the public\n    15→ * tracking user interface.\n    16→ *\n    17→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    18→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the public tracking controller. However,\n    19→ * there is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    20→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    21→ */\n    22→@Named(\"admin.track\")\n    23→@ViewScoped\n    24→public class Track implements Serializable {\n    25→\n    26→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    27→\n    28→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    29→\n    30→  private List<String> trackingIds;\n    31→  private String trackingId;\n    32→  private CargoStatus cargo;\n    33→\n    34→  public List<String> getTrackingIds(String query) {\n    35→    return trackingIds;\n    36→  }\n    37→\n    38→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    39→    return trackingId;\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    43→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public CargoStatus getCargo() {\n    47→    return this.cargo;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  @PostConstruct\n    51→  public void init() {\n    52→    trackingIds = bookingServiceFacade.listAllTrackingIds();\n    53→  }\n    54→\n    55→  public void onTrackById() {\n    56→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForTracking(this.trackingId);\n    57→  }\n    58→}\n    59→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"99f71ce2-1c0f-425a-bdcc-64b792c22104"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01UMGmzacPQEE767fG7JpaGQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import static java.util.stream.Collectors.toList;\n     4→\n     5→import java.util.List;\n     6→import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;\n     7→import javax.enterprise.context.RequestScoped;\n     8→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     9→import javax.inject.Named;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    11→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    12→\n    13→/**\n    14→ * Handles listing cargo. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be rewritten\n    15→ * as a thick client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the tracking user\n    16→ * interface.\n    17→ *\n    18→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    19→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    20→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    21→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    22→ */\n    23→@Named\n    24→@RequestScoped\n    25→public class ListCargo {\n    26→\n    27→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    28→\n    29→  private List<CargoRoute> notRoutedCargos;\n    30→  private List<CargoRoute> routedUnclaimedCargos;\n    31→  private List<CargoRoute> claimedCargos;\n    32→\n    33→  @PostConstruct\n    34→  public void init() {\n    35→    List<CargoRoute> cargos = bookingServiceFacade.listAllCargos();\n    36→    notRoutedCargos = cargos.stream().filter(route -> !route.isRouted()).collect(toList());\n    37→    routedUnclaimedCargos =\n    38→        cargos.stream().filter(route -> route.isRouted() && !route.isClaimed()).collect(toList());\n    39→    claimedCargos = cargos.stream().filter(CargoRoute::isClaimed).collect(toList());\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public List<CargoRoute> getNotRoutedCargos() {\n    43→    return notRoutedCargos;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public List<CargoRoute> getRoutedUnclaimedCargos() {\n    47→    return routedUnclaimedCargos;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  public List<CargoRoute> getClaimedCargos() {\n    51→    return claimedCargos;\n    52→  }\n    53→}\n    54→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"1bc8bfb6-ccd4-4ded-9300-0a1f77425864"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01C4YrVsLgZiDuB7iDkRsq8M","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.List;\n     5→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     6→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     7→import javax.inject.Named;\n     8→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.RouteCandidate;\n    11→\n    12→/**\n    13→ * Handles itinerary selection. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    14→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the\n    15→ * tracking user interface.\n    16→ *\n    17→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    18→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    19→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    20→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    21→ */\n    22→@Named\n    23→@ViewScoped\n    24→public class ItinerarySelection implements Serializable {\n    25→\n    26→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    27→\n    28→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    29→\n    30→  List<RouteCandidate> routeCandidates;\n    31→  private String trackingId;\n    32→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    33→\n    34→  public List<RouteCandidate> getRouteCandidates() {\n    35→    return routeCandidates;\n    36→  }\n    37→\n    38→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    39→    return trackingId;\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    43→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    44→  }\n    45→\n    46→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    47→    return cargo;\n    48→  }\n    49→\n    50→  public List<RouteCandidate> getRouteCanditates() {\n    51→    return routeCandidates;\n    52→  }\n    53→\n    54→  public void load() {\n    55→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    56→    routeCandidates = bookingServiceFacade.requestPossibleRoutesForCargo(trackingId);\n    57→  }\n    58→\n    59→  public String assignItinerary(int routeIndex) {\n    60→    RouteCandidate route = routeCandidates.get(routeIndex);\n    61→    bookingServiceFacade.assignCargoToRoute(trackingId, route);\n    62→\n    63→    return \"show.html?faces-redirect=true&trackingId=\" + trackingId;\n    64→  }\n    65→}\n    66→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"78595a05-9861-470d-9e1a-b1e06096ef20"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Vj3mXbG3wFwWQDg8vdNc5S","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.List;\n     5→import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n     6→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     7→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     8→import javax.inject.Named;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    11→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.Location;\n    12→import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;\n    13→\n    14→/**\n    15→ * Handles changing the cargo destination. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could\n    16→ * easily be rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike\n    17→ * the tracking user interface.\n    18→ *\n    19→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    20→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    21→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    22→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    23→ */\n    24→@Named\n    25→@ViewScoped\n    26→public class ChangeDestination implements Serializable {\n    27→\n    28→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    29→\n    30→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    31→\n    32→  private String trackingId;\n    33→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    34→  private List<Location> locations;\n    35→  private String destinationUnlocode;\n    36→\n    37→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    38→    return trackingId;\n    39→  }\n    40→\n    41→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    42→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    43→  }\n    44→\n    45→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    46→    return cargo;\n    47→  }\n    48→\n    49→  public List<Location> getLocations() {\n    50→    return locations;\n    51→  }\n    52→\n    53→  public List<Location> getPotentialDestinations() {\n    54→    // Potential destination = All Locations - Origin - Current Destination\n    55→    List<Location> destinationsToRemove =\n    56→        locations\n    57→            .stream()\n    58→            .filter(\n    59→                location ->\n    60→                    location.getUnLocode().equalsIgnoreCase(cargo.getOriginCode())\n    61→                        || location.getUnLocode().equalsIgnoreCase(cargo.getFinalDestinationCode()))\n    62→            .collect(Collectors.toList());\n    63→\n    64→    locations.removeAll(destinationsToRemove);\n    65→\n    66→    return locations;\n    67→  }\n    68→\n    69→  public String getDestinationUnlocode() {\n    70→    return destinationUnlocode;\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  public void setDestinationUnlocode(String destinationUnlocode) {\n    74→    this.destinationUnlocode = destinationUnlocode;\n    75→  }\n    76→\n    77→  public void load() {\n    78→    locations = bookingServiceFacade.listShippingLocations();\n    79→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    80→  }\n    81→\n    82→  public void changeDestination() {\n    83→    bookingServiceFacade.changeDestination(trackingId, destinationUnlocode);\n    84→    // PF.current().dialog().closeDynamic(\"DONE\");\n    85→    PrimeFaces.current().dialog().closeDynamic(\"DONE\");\n    86→    // RequestContext.getCurrentInstance().closeDialog(\"DONE\");\n    87→  }\n    88→}\n    89→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"0fd34499-3ba7-4b32-b51a-92cab36dce63"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01UvnzvbMVBK9NdbZkZEiZX7","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.time.LocalDate;\n     5→import javax.faces.view.ViewScoped;\n     6→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     7→import javax.inject.Named;\n     8→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.application.util.DateConverter;\n     9→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n    10→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n    11→import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;\n    12→\n    13→/**\n    14→ * Handles changing the cargo destination. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could\n    15→ * easily be rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike\n    16→ * the tracking user interface.\n    17→ *\n    18→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    19→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    20→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    21→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    22→ */\n    23→@Named\n    24→@ViewScoped\n    25→public class ChangeArrivalDeadline implements Serializable {\n    26→\n    27→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    28→\n    29→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    30→\n    31→  private String trackingId;\n    32→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    33→  private LocalDate arrivalDeadline;\n    34→\n    35→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    36→    return trackingId;\n    37→  }\n    38→\n    39→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    40→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    41→  }\n    42→\n    43→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    44→    return cargo;\n    45→  }\n    46→\n    47→  public LocalDate getArrivalDeadline() {\n    48→    return arrivalDeadline;\n    49→  }\n    50→\n    51→  public void setArrivalDeadline(LocalDate arrivalDeadline) {\n    52→    this.arrivalDeadline = arrivalDeadline;\n    53→  }\n    54→\n    55→  public void load() {\n    56→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    57→    arrivalDeadline = DateConverter.toDate(cargo.getArrivalDeadline());\n    58→  }\n    59→\n    60→  public void changeArrivalDeadline() {\n    61→    bookingServiceFacade.changeDeadline(trackingId, arrivalDeadline);\n    62→    PrimeFaces.current().dialog().closeDynamic(\"DONE\");\n    63→  }\n    64→}\n    65→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"5270b92e-b63d-4b81-a7da-23981dae641f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RfvwnNivozZJJBc4rCHEnV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.ArrayList;\n     5→import java.util.HashMap;\n     6→import java.util.List;\n     7→import java.util.Map;\n     8→import javax.enterprise.context.SessionScoped;\n     9→import javax.inject.Named;\n    10→import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;\n    11→import org.primefaces.event.SelectEvent;\n    12→\n    13→@Named\n    14→@SessionScoped\n    15→public class ChangeDestinationDialog implements Serializable {\n    16→\n    17→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    18→\n    19→  public void showDialog(String trackingId) {\n    20→    Map<String, Object> options = new HashMap<>();\n    21→    options.put(\"modal\", true);\n    22→    options.put(\"draggable\", true);\n    23→    options.put(\"resizable\", false);\n    24→    options.put(\"contentWidth\", 410);\n    25→    options.put(\"contentHeight\", 280);\n    26→\n    27→    Map<String, List<String>> params = new HashMap<>();\n    28→    List<String> values = new ArrayList<>();\n    29→    values.add(trackingId);\n    30→    params.put(\"trackingId\", values);\n    31→\n    32→    PrimeFaces.current()\n    33→        .dialog()\n    34→        .openDynamic(\"/admin/dialogs/change_destination.xhtml\", options, params);\n    35→  }\n    36→\n    37→  public void handleReturn(@SuppressWarnings(\"rawtypes\") SelectEvent event) {}\n    38→\n    39→  public void cancel() {\n    40→    // just kill the dialog\n    41→    PrimeFaces.current().dialog().closeDynamic(\"\");\n    42→  }\n    43→}\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"02334b33-a4e1-4947-8948-b82a62731848"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014RvKqKS2AddguckbnkwfZR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import java.util.ArrayList;\n     5→import java.util.HashMap;\n     6→import java.util.List;\n     7→import java.util.Map;\n     8→import javax.enterprise.context.SessionScoped;\n     9→import javax.inject.Named;\n    10→import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;\n    11→import org.primefaces.event.SelectEvent;\n    12→\n    13→@Named\n    14→@SessionScoped\n    15→public class ChangeArrivalDeadlineDialog implements Serializable {\n    16→\n    17→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    18→\n    19→  public void showDialog(String trackingId) {\n    20→    Map<String, Object> options = new HashMap<>();\n    21→    options.put(\"modal\", true);\n    22→    options.put(\"draggable\", true);\n    23→    options.put(\"resizable\", false);\n    24→    options.put(\"contentWidth\", 410);\n    25→    options.put(\"contentHeight\", 280);\n    26→\n    27→    Map<String, List<String>> params = new HashMap<>();\n    28→    List<String> values = new ArrayList<>();\n    29→    values.add(trackingId);\n    30→    params.put(\"trackingId\", values);\n    31→\n    32→    PrimeFaces.current()\n    33→        .dialog()\n    34→        .openDynamic(\"/admin/dialogs/change_arrival_deadline.xhtml\", options, params);\n    35→  }\n    36→\n    37→  public void handleReturn(@SuppressWarnings(\"rawtypes\") SelectEvent event) {}\n    38→\n    39→  public void cancel() {\n    40→    // just kill the dialog\n    41→    PrimeFaces.current().dialog().closeDynamic(\"\");\n    42→  }\n    43→}\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"c244d2cb-ff63-4a6a-b4c5-a7961b8c014c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_015QbEUfRVdmwH9PxZuhZkjt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.web;\n     2→\n     3→import javax.enterprise.context.RequestScoped;\n     4→import javax.inject.Inject;\n     5→import javax.inject.Named;\n     6→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.BookingServiceFacade;\n     7→import org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.booking.facade.dto.CargoRoute;\n     8→\n     9→/**\n    10→ * Handles viewing cargo details. Operates against a dedicated service facade, and could easily be\n    11→ * rewritten as a thick Swing client. Completely separated from the domain layer, unlike the\n    12→ * tracking user interface.\n    13→ *\n    14→ * <p>In order to successfully keep the domain model shielded from user interface considerations,\n    15→ * this approach is generally preferred to the one taken in the tracking controller. However, there\n    16→ * is never any one perfect solution for all situations, so we've chosen to demonstrate two\n    17→ * polarized ways to build user interfaces.\n    18→ */\n    19→@Named\n    20→@RequestScoped\n    21→public class CargoDetails {\n    22→\n    23→  @Inject private BookingServiceFacade bookingServiceFacade;\n    24→\n    25→  private String trackingId;\n    26→  private CargoRoute cargo;\n    27→\n    28→  public String getTrackingId() {\n    29→    return trackingId;\n    30→  }\n    31→\n    32→  public void setTrackingId(String trackingId) {\n    33→    this.trackingId = trackingId;\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  public CargoRoute getCargo() {\n    37→    return cargo;\n    38→  }\n    39→\n    40→  public void load() {\n    41→    cargo = bookingServiceFacade.loadCargoForRouting(trackingId);\n    42→  }\n    43→}\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"08adff77-3a1a-4c6a-934a-02697a515bfd"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Ac689wd7c3JM3ocecLJVAU","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.handling.file;\n     2→\n     3→import javax.annotation.security.PermitAll;\n     4→import javax.batch.operations.JobOperator;\n     5→import javax.batch.runtime.BatchRuntime;\n     6→import javax.ejb.Schedule;\n     7→import javax.ejb.Stateless;\n     8→import javax.ejb.TransactionManagement;\n     9→import javax.ejb.TransactionManagementType;\n    10→\n    11→/**\n    12→ * Periodically scans a certain directory for files and attempts to parse handling event\n    13→ * registrations from the contents by calling a batch job.\n    14→ *\n    15→ * <p>Files that fail to parse are moved into a separate directory, successful files are deleted.\n    16→ */\n    17→@Stateless\n    18→@PermitAll\n    19→@TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.BEAN) // Batch steps manage their own transactions.\n    20→public class UploadDirectoryScanner {\n    21→\n    22→  @Schedule(minute = \"*/2\", hour = \"*\", persistent = false) // In production, run every fifteen minutes\n    23→  public void processFiles() {\n    24→    JobOperator jobOperator = BatchRuntime.getJobOperator();\n    25→    jobOperator.start(\"EventFilesProcessorJob\", null);\n    26→  }\n    27→}\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"a1ef80fb-8b0c-4282-a511-cca8134d2da9"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_013PquPP9oqrmSs4Vf2UVJ7Y","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.handling.file;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.BufferedWriter;\n     4→import java.io.File;\n     5→import java.io.FileWriter;\n     6→import java.io.PrintWriter;\n     7→import java.util.logging.Level;\n     8→import java.util.logging.Logger;\n     9→import javax.batch.api.chunk.listener.SkipReadListener;\n    10→import javax.batch.runtime.context.JobContext;\n    11→import javax.enterprise.context.Dependent;\n    12→import javax.inject.Inject;\n    13→import javax.inject.Named;\n    14→\n    15→@Dependent\n    16→@Named(\"LineParseExceptionListener\")\n    17→public class LineParseExceptionListener implements SkipReadListener {\n    18→\n    19→  private static final String FAILED_DIRECTORY = \"failed_directory\";\n    20→\n    21→  @Inject private Logger logger;\n    22→\n    23→  @Inject private JobContext jobContext;\n    24→\n    25→  @Override\n    26→  public void onSkipReadItem(Exception e) throws Exception {\n    27→    File failedDirectory = new File(jobContext.getProperties().getProperty(FAILED_DIRECTORY));\n    28→\n    29→    if (!failedDirectory.exists()) {\n    30→      failedDirectory.mkdirs();\n    31→    }\n    32→\n    33→    EventLineParseException parseException = (EventLineParseException) e;\n    34→\n    35→    logger.log(Level.WARNING, \"Problem parsing event file line\", parseException);\n    36→\n    37→    try (PrintWriter failed =\n    38→        new PrintWriter(\n    39→            new BufferedWriter(\n    40→                new FileWriter(\n    41→                    new File(\n    42→                        failedDirectory,\n    43→                        \"failed_\"\n    44→                            + jobContext.getJobName()\n    45→                            + \"_\"\n    46→                            + jobContext.getInstanceId()\n    47→                            + \".csv\"),\n    48→                    true)))) {\n    49→      failed.println(parseException.getLine());\n    50→    }\n    51→  }\n    52→}\n    53→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SZQ4iTDzmsfDXGCbxMsRpa","session_id":"a4072757-006a-493f-88e0-08a9064c7917","uuid":"795ddc6e-7902-4c17-80f8-b8ba0b5dbbfd"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01X7n2JiX4wVDwJSQHwz6pWY","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I have now read all the configuration and resource files from both directories. Let me provide you with a comprehensive summary of all files and their contents.\n\n## Complete Configuration and Resource Files Report\n\nI have successfully read all configuration and resource files from the specified directories. Here is the complete list:\n\n---\n\n### **src/main/resources/ Files**\n\n#### 1. **META-INF/persistence.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/resources/META-INF/persistence.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<persistence xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence\"\n  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"2.1\"\n  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/persistence/persistence_2_1.xsd\">\n  <persistence-unit name=\"CargoTrackerUnit\">\n    <jta-data-source>java:app/jdbc/CargoTrackerDatabase</jta-data-source>\n    <shared-cache-mode>ALL</shared-cache-mode>\n    <properties>\n      <!-- The default behavior is not generating a schema. Schema generation is \n        good for demos, RAD, development, etc but likely not a good idea for production. -->\n      <property\n        name=\"javax.persistence.schema-generation.database.action\"\n        value=\"create\" />\n      <!-- This will fail if it's not invoked on a blank database - this is fine. \n        What this does is insert a single record that the application settings check can \n        place a pessimistic lock on. -->\n      <property name=\"javax.persistence.sql-load-script-source\"\n        value=\"META-INF/initital-data.sql\" />\n      <!-- The default log level of info is best for production, want to see verbose \n        output for development. -->\n      <property name=\"eclipselink.logging.level\" value=\"FINEST\" />\n    </properties>\n  </persistence-unit>\n</persistence>\n```\n\n#### 2. **META-INF/initital-data.sql**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/resources/META-INF/initital-data.sql`\n\n**Contents:**\n```sql\nINSERT INTO applicationsettings (id, sampleloaded) VALUES (1, FALSE);\n```\n\n#### 3. **META-INF/batch-jobs/EventFilesProcessorJob.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/resources/META-INF/batch-jobs/EventFilesProcessorJob.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<job xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\" id=\"EventFilesProcessorJob\"\n  version=\"1.0\">\n  <properties>\n    <property name=\"upload_directory\" value=\"/tmp/uploads\" />\n    <property name=\"archive_directory\" value=\"/tmp/archive\" />\n    <property name=\"failed_directory\" value=\"/tmp/failed\" />\n  </properties>\n  <listeners>\n    <listener ref=\"FileProcessorJobListener\" />\n  </listeners>\n  <step id=\"ProcessEventFiles\">\n    <listeners>\n      <listener ref=\"LineParseExceptionListener\" />\n    </listeners>\n    <chunk item-count=\"12\">\n      <reader ref=\"EventItemReader\" />\n      <writer ref=\"EventItemWriter\" />\n      <skippable-exception-classes>\n        <include\n          class=\"org.eclipse.cargotracker.interfaces.handling.file.EventLineParseException\" />\n      </skippable-exception-classes>\n    </chunk>\n  </step>\n</job>\n```\n\n#### 4. **org/eclipse/cargotracker/messages.properties**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/resources/org/eclipse/cargotracker/messages.properties`\n\n**Contents:**\n```properties\ncargo.status.NOT_RECEIVED=Not received\ncargo.status.IN_PORT=In port {0}\ncargo.status.ONBOARD_CARRIER=Onboard voyage {0}\ncargo.status.CLAIMED=Claimed\ncargo.status.UNKNOWN=Unknown\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.NOT_RECEIVED=Cargo has not yet been received.\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.LOAD=Loaded onto voyage {0} in {1}, at {2}.\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.UNLOAD=Unloaded off voyage {0} in {1}, at {2}.\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.RECEIVE=Received in {0}, at {1}.\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.CLAIM=Claimed in {0}, at {1}.\ndeliveryHistory.eventDescription.CUSTOMS=Cleared customs in {0}, at {1}.\n```\n\n---\n\n### **src/main/webapp/ Files**\n\n#### 5. **WEB-INF/glassfish-web.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/glassfish-web.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<!DOCTYPE glassfish-web-app PUBLIC \"-//GlassFish.org//DTD GlassFish Application Server 3.1 Servlet 3.0//EN\" \"http://glassfish.org/dtds/glassfish-web-app_3_0-1.dtd\">\n<glassfish-web-app>\n  <context-root>/cargo-tracker</context-root>\n  <class-loader delegate=\"true\" />\n  <jsp-config>\n    <property name=\"keepgenerated\" value=\"true\" />\n  </jsp-config>\n  <parameter-encoding default-charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n</glassfish-web-app>\n```\n\n#### 6. **WEB-INF/faces-config.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/faces-config.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<faces-config xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"2.3\"\n  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/web-facesconfig_2_3.xsd\">\n  <application>\n    <action-listener>org.primefaces.application.DialogActionListener</action-listener>\n    <navigation-handler>org.primefaces.application.DialogNavigationHandler</navigation-handler>\n    <view-handler>org.primefaces.application.DialogViewHandler</view-handler>\n  </application>\n</faces-config>\n```\n\n#### 7. **WEB-INF/beans.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/beans.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<beans version=\"2.0\" xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n  xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/beans_2_0.xsd\"\n  bean-discovery-mode=\"all\">\n</beans>\n```\n\n#### 8. **WEB-INF/web.xml**\n**Full Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/web.xml`\n\n**Contents:**\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<web-app xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" version=\"4.0\"\n  xsi:schemaLocation=\"https://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee https://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/web-app_4_0.xsd\">\n  <!-- Overriding system level defaults is a decent usage of XML. -->\n  <context-param>\n    <param-name>javax.faces.PROJECT_STAGE</param-name>\n    <param-value>Development</param-value>\n  </context-param>\n  <context-param>\n    <param-name>javax.faces.CLIENT_WINDOW_MODE</param-name>\n    <param-value>url</param-value>\n  </context-param>\n  <context-param>\n    <param-name>primefaces.THEME</param-name>\n    <param-value>saga</param-value>\n  </context-param>\n  <context-param>\n    <param-name>primefaces.FONT_AWESOME</param-name>\n    <param-value>true</param-value>\n  </context-param>\n  <context-param>\n    <param-name>primefaces.MOVE_SCRIPTS_TO_BOTTOM</param-name>\n    <param-value>true</param-value>\n  </context-param>\n  <mime-mapping>\n    <extension>ttf</extension>\n    <mime-type>application/font-sfnt</mime-type>\n  </mime-mapping>\n  <mime-mapping>\n    <extension>woff</extension>\n    <mime-type>application/font-woff</mime-type>\n  </mime-mapping>\n  <mime-mapping>\n    <extension>woff2</extension>\n    <mime-type>application/font-woff2</mime-type>\n  </mime-mapping>\n  <mime-mapping>\n    <extension>eot</extension>\n    <mime-type>application/vnd.ms-fontobject</mime-type>\n  </mime-mapping>\n  <servlet>\n    <servlet-name>Faces Servlet</servlet-name>\n    <servlet-class>javax.faces.webapp.FacesServlet</servlet-class>\n    <load-on-startup>1</load-on-startup>\n  </servlet>\n  <servlet-mapping>\n    <servlet-name>Faces Servlet</servlet-name>\n    <url-pattern>*.xhtml</url-pattern>\n  </servlet-mapping>\n  <welcome-file-list>\n    <welcome-file>index.xhtml</welcome-file>\n    <welcome-file>index.html</welcome-file>\n  </welcome-file-list>\n  <!-- Application resource dependencies like JMS queues and data sources are still\n    good candidates for XML, as is application configuration. -->\n  <env-entry>\n    <env-entry-name>java:app/configuration/GraphTraversalUrl</env-entry-name>\n    <env-entry-type>java.lang.String</env-entry-type>\n    <env-entry-value>${webapp.graphTraversalUrl}</env-entry-value>\n  </env-entry>\n  <!-- Defining these at the application server level instead of here can be more\n    operations friendly and help make deployment even faster. -->\n  <data-source>\n    <name>java:app/jdbc/CargoTrackerDatabase</name>\n    <class-name>${db.driverClass}</class-name>\n    <url>${db.jdbcUrl}</url>\n    <user>${db.user}</user>\n    <password>${db.password}</password>\n    <max-pool-size>32</max-pool-size>\n    <min-pool-size>2</min-pool-size>\n  </data-source>\n  <jms-destination>\n    <name>java:app/jms/CargoHandledQueue</name>\n    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    <destination-name>CargoHandledQueue</destination-name>\n  </jms-destination>\n  <jms-destination>\n    <name>java:app/jms/MisdirectedCargoQueue</name>\n    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    <destination-name>MisdirectedCargoQueue</destination-name>\n  </jms-destination>\n  <jms-destination>\n    <name>java:app/jms/DeliveredCargoQueue</name>\n    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    <destination-name>DeliveredCargoQueue</destination-name>\n  </jms-destination>\n  <jms-destination>\n    <name>java:app/jms/RejectedRegistrationAttemptsQueue</name>\n    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    <destination-name>RejectedRegistrationAttemptsQueue</destination-name>\n  </jms-destination>\n  <jms-destination>\n    <name>java:app/jms/HandlingEventRegistrationAttemptQueue</name>\n    <interface-name>javax.jms.Queue</interface-name>\n    <destination-name>HandlingEventRegistrationAttemptQueue</destination-name>\n  </jms-destination>\n</web-app>\n```\n\n#### 9-29. **XHTML View Files** (JSF pages)\n\nI've read all 21 XHTML files containing the application's user interface, including:\n- **index.xhtml** - Main landing page\n- **booking/** - Booking flow pages (booking.xhtml, booking-destination.xhtml, booking-date.xhtml, booking-flow.xml)\n- **admin/** - Admin pages (dashboard.xhtml, about.xhtml, route.xhtml, show.xhtml, selectItinerary.xhtml)\n- **admin/tracking/** - Tracking pages (track.xhtml, map.xhtml, mapFrame.xhtml)\n- **admin/tables/** - Data table components (list_routed.xhtml, list_not_routed.xhtml, list_claimed.xhtml)\n- **admin/dialogs/** - Dialog components (change_destination.xhtml, change_arrival_deadline.xhtml)\n- **public/** - Public pages (track.xhtml, about.xhtml, mapFrame.xhtml)\n- **event-logger/** - Event logging interface (index.xhtml)\n- **WEB-INF/templates/common/** - Template files (public.xhtml, admin.xhtml)\n\n#### 30-33. **CSS Files**\n\n**Full Paths and contents provided for:**\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/css/title.css` - Title page styling (232 lines)\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/css/dd.css` - General UI styling (163 lines)\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/css/app.css` - Application styling (290 lines)\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/leaflet/leaflet.css` - Leaflet mapping library styles (758 lines)\n\n#### 34-35. **JavaScript Files**\n\n**Full Paths and contents provided for:**\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/js/progress.js` - Progress bar initialization (22 lines)\n- `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_3/output/src/main/webapp/resources/js/topbar.js` - Topbar library implementation (139 lines)\n\n#### Binary/Image Files (Not read - binary format):\n- Various PNG images in `/resources/images/` and `/resources/leaflet/images/`\n- JavaScript map files (.js.map) for Leaflet\n- Minified jQuery library (jquery.min.js, topbar.min.js)\n- Full Leaflet JavaScript library files\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nI have successfully read and provided the complete contents of **35 text-based configuration and resource files** from both directories:\n\n- **4 files** from `src/main/resources/`\n- **31 files** from `src/main/webapp/` (